text:
This is just my first experience at this place.
I paid $65 for a birthday special table reservation for 3 people  that was supposed to include the birthday table decoration, 1 bottle of Champagne and Happy Birthday singing for the birthday man  right after the dinner. This is what happened:

**The hostess took us to the wrong table in a careless way. Then she lied to us saying she didn't do it. Not even an apology. It may be normal there.

**The server came to get the order of drinks. She never mentioned anything about a birthday celebration or Champagne**

**I asked for the bottle of Champagne that was supposed to be on the table, the she brought it with almost no ice on the ice bucket**

**You would think that the server will offer to serve the Champagne. Forget it!   She just put the bucket on the table like working in Amazon's warehouse.

**The hostess told me that "the Bday singing will only happen after we finish with dinner". ...I shouldn't believe her. .... A server boy started to noisily play a drum bothering every guest in that place. It seems like he was calling the other servers to start singing for every Bday table one next to the other until that came to my table when we were in the middle of dinner with our mouths full of food.** The Bday ceremony was totally ruined.

The check:
They included a charge of a "Large party" to my bill ($13). It was a party of 3. My server never told me about it. I asked to another server and she told me that it is an automatic service charge for guests who stay dancing after dinner. A Large Party charge for a Party of 3 people.(Of course that the owner (s) and managers are  aware of it.

If you like just to get drunk and dance with good but very noisy popular music, this is the right place for you.

I don't think there was a single manager in this place that cared about excellence of service. I never saw a manager going to tables.

Food was good and I saw another server giving an excellent service to the table next to me.

I hope this was only a coincidence on my visit.

Hopefully one day I can modify this review.!

text: Great Food, Great service!!! Friendly, beautiful day sitting outside, canâ€™t say enough positive things about the food and the service!! Looking forward to coming back

A Culinary Journey at Brinehouse: Where Bold Flavors Meet Refined Craft

From the moment the Steak Rustler arrived at our table, it was clear that Brinehouse in Safety Harbor understands the art of flavor composition. This isn't just a steakhouse dishâ€”it's a carefully orchestrated symphony of tastes that speaks to both Southern comfort and culinary innovation.

The star of the evening was undoubtedly the steak itself, cooked to perfection with a beautiful char that locked in every bit of its natural richness. But what elevated this dish from excellent to extraordinary was the inspired pairing of pimento cheese and poblano peppers. The creamy, tangy pimento cheese brought a luxurious texture and nostalgic warmth, while the poblano peppers added a subtle heat and earthy complexity that danced across the palate. Each bite revealed new layersâ€”the smokiness of the peppers playing against the sharpness of the cheese, all while the perfectly seasoned steak anchored the experience with its robust, satisfying presence.

The Antipasto Salad served as the ideal counterpoint to the richness of the Steak Rustler. Fresh, vibrant, and thoughtfully composed, this wasn't your standard saladâ€”it was a celebration of texture and acidity. The pickled vegetables brought a bright, tangy punch that awakened the palate, while the fresh ingredients provided crisp contrast and garden-fresh flavor. It's the kind of dish that reminds you why great restaurants pay attention to every course, not just the main event.

What impressed me most about this meal was the balance. Brinehouse has mastered the delicate art of creating dishes that are simultaneously bold and refined, comforting yet sophisticated. The kitchen clearly respects quality ingredients while having the confidence to push flavor boundaries.

For anyone seeking an elevated dining experience in Safety Harbor, Brinehouse delivers not just a meal, but a memorable culinary journey worth savoring.

text:
Itâ€™s been a few days, I donâ€™t like leaving negative reviews, but this one has been haunting me. Iâ€™m only writing this because this place has a reputation as one of the nicest places in town and I just canâ€™t stand for that. To those who are used to boring basic corporate food delivered restaurant food then I guess this place is fine. However it is far far far from a fine dining experience. I had a mid lunch here a year or so ago and was never inspired to come back. This weekend however my sister informed me that we were having my mothers birthday here. So I was excited to give it another chance, never again.

Firstly; she made reservations a week and a half in advance and we had literally the worst table in the place. We were seated right next to the entrance along the pathway for not only the servers to run to the kitchen, but also for all of the outdoor guests to come in to use the restroom. The place was half empty on a sunday afternoon with more than several other options to seat us more comfortably. I discovered this though too late as my group had already been seated. You see I had just spent 24 min outside waiting for the valet parking attendant. I asked the guests who were leaving and they told me that they too had been waiting just over a half hour to get their car back.

Well I put on a smile and joined the family, determined to have a positive experience. I ordered the croque monsieur and was sadly disappointed.  The menu listed it as being on sourdough and with bÃ©chamel sauce. It was made with what looked and tasted like thick cut texas toast, white fluffy and bland. The opposite of sourdough. The lack of sauce made even more present by the dryness of the bread. It was served with fries, ?!? Traditionally this comes with a side salad with a french or balsamic dressing, a perfect crisp bite in contrast to the salty cheese on the sandwich. The fries were too much, mire salt carbs and grease? Who out that together. Also it is not as though the fries were anything to write home about. In fact they were some of the blandest Iâ€™ve ever seen, quite obviously frozen from a corporate food delivery. I looked over at my sisterâ€™s dish and I could tell her salmon was cheap and colored as well, her stomach ache later that day finishing off what I assumed. My other sister ordered a pizza and the server didnâ€™t think to tell her it was a full size to serve three or four people. Who is that unaware?

Talking about the server she did something I have never seen a server do before. And this is really why Iâ€™m writing this. This place sells itâ€™s self as upscale and the largest part of an upscale experience to me is the service. Here it obviously wasnâ€™t the food. She complimented my mother on her ring and then proceeded to grab her hand and pull it up closer for her to look at. My mom was thrown off, getting a compliment but simultaneously getting manhandled with this stranger in her personal space. She then grabbed at the necklace she was wearing and touched her earrings. Who does that?!? A total disrespect of personal space and boundaries and a complete disregard of her position as our server.

Lastly several of my party asked for some things to go. And instead of taking the items to the kitchen and preparing them all for them, she brought the bags out and made everyone pack their own to go bags! How on earth does this place have the rating it has? Just because they put wood paneling up and French looking tiles.

I highly DO NOT recommend this place. Look around the area, this town has an over abundance of restaurants far superior to what one gets here.

And lastly, I want to point out how sad is it that the place is literally walking distance from one of the bay areaâ€™s best organic farmers markets, and they donâ€™t take advantage of it at all. Such a missed opportunity to offer the quality they claim to provide.

text:
Mr. Dunderbakâ€™s is more than just a restaurant itâ€™s a time capsule of authentic German heritage and flavor. From the first bite to the last sip, every dish carries the same old-world quality and attention to detail that made their original University Square Mall location such a Tampa landmark. The sausages, the sauerkraut, the fresh-baked pretzels, and that unmistakable aroma of imported beer and grilled goodness instantly brought me back to my childhood.

The staff are friendly, the portions are generous, and the atmosphere feels like stepping into a cozy Bavarian tavern. Itâ€™s rare to find a place that stays true to its roots while still evolving with the times. Mr. Dunderbakâ€™s continues to do just that serving up memories as rich as the flavors on every plate.

If you grew up in Tampa and remember the old location, you owe it to yourself to relive that experience again. A truly authentic gem that stands the test of time.

I absolutely love schnitzel. The food here is good and you won't be disappointed, but I recently acquired a mammalian meat allergy due to a tick bite and I can only eat chicken and seafood. I've messaged them to their email address and on their social media probably seven times over the last two years asking them to please add a chicken schnitzel to their menu, but I never hear back from them. I know I would be asking for a lot for them to add a menu item just for me, but I also think a lot of people other than just me would enjoy a chicken schnitzel option. The lack of any response or any communication, even just to say, "no, we're not going to do that", is frustrating.

text:
There is celebrated history for my family aligning with German culture as my oldest daughter was born in Bavarian Germany.  So naturally, we try our best to find the local German cuisine and festivities everywhere that we travel and live. Luckily for us, we discovered Mr. Dunderbak's, which wasn't incredibly too far from Lutz.

We came mid-afternoon on a Sunday and the parking lot was full - fortunately, we were able to find some spots without waiting too long. As it was the end of September, Mr. Dunderbak's also hosted some Oktoberfest observations and festivities. This meant a bit of a wait for our family of four to be seated inside, but it was worth it!

As you walk up to the restaurant, you are greeted with the unique Bavarian-esque calligraphy of its name in bold, golden hue. There was still outdoor seating available when we went in the form of tables and  benches that situated in the parking spaces in front of the venue. Approaching the entrance, you will encounter a set of oaken doors that set the stage for your welcome. The doors then open up to a short corridor that which is adorned with wall hangings and lined with cases of beer along its walls, while the incandescent lighting contribute to the tone and ambiance of the restaurant before opening up to the immersive dining space.

Immediately, we were reminded of our time spent living in Germany, as well as our travels to Austria. The noise-level was definitely suited for the space and environment that you find at a Biergarten. While the lighting was somewhat dim, the atmosphere was lively and vibrant which didn't rely on the light musical faire playing in the backdrop. There was a playful arrangement of seating areas - from biergarten benches and tables to formal tables with even a dining table under a gazebo centered in the dining space - making Mr. Dunderbak's even more festive. Flanking either side of the main dining space were two smaller rooms, with a full bar.

What makes Mr. Dunderbak's even more unique is the mini-store that lines around the main dining space, along with a fully operational deli, offering an assortment of German meats/sausages and groceries (comparable to the Cracker Barrel concept, but better and without the negative media).

As for the food, we definitely were able to satisfy our German-cuisine cravings. The menu was rather robust offering a variety of schnitzels and wursts (yes, they have currywurst), while offering a unique American flare with their other menu items. While I did not get any beer to accompany my meal, my wife ordered a Radler - and a grapefruit one at that - which arguably made her day. The jagerschnitzel, sauerkraut, and potato salad were solid, while the nurnberger (wursts) and spatzle were a hit with my kids.

Overall, we had a great experience at Mr. Dunderbak's and will definitely be back again. This is a great place to go with groups and to simply enjoy company! Prost!

text: I really hate to write this review as I have been coming to this restaurant for 20 years, back even when it was at University Mall. The food and service has always been great, as it was today as well. What made it a horrible experience was the actions of one of the owners. When my husband and I sat down at the bar, the woman owner was washing dishes and began yelling at the hostess for moving a paycheck that was sitting on the bar as she sat us. We then watched her berate her staff multiple times, but we could not take it when she threw a glass of water on one of her staff. I was hit with that water and at that point, my husband had to say something. We told her that she was abusing her staff and being incredibly disrespectful to them. She began to complain about fighting with the manager. The fact that one of the owners would act like that in the front of the house, in front of customers, is one of the most unprofessional things my husband and I have seen in a restaurant. The poor manager and other servers/bartenders should not have to work in that kind of hostile and abusive environment. The owner does not have to be in the building, and she would serve it best by never stepping inside it again. The other owner, whom we briefly spoke to apologized to us, but he needs to do more to protect his staff from this unhinged woman. The only reason this restaurant has survived all of these years and has been successful is due to it's hard-working employees. To think an owner would denigrate them, and in front of customers no less, is abhorant. We will not be back to this restaurant, which is unfortunate because we love the food, service, and atmosphere. To see an owner, so hateful to the people that has made her and the other owner successful is truly heartbreaking.
Best Germany restaurant in Tampa. Must visit especially during Octoberfest. Come see accordion Joe.

text:
Deeply Disappointing Experience for Our Small Wedding

I hosted my wedding (50 guests) at The Columbia two years ago, and I still canâ€™t get over how poorly we were treated. From the moment I paid the final deposit â€” which was half of the total bill â€” the cooperation ended.

When I asked for a reasonable amount of time to set up before the ceremony, I was told two hours was the maximum, and when I explained that wasnâ€™t enough, the coordinator replied that â€œmost people have a wedding planner.â€ My friends tried to help with setup but were not allowed into the reserved space at the agreed-upon time, so almost nothing got done. It created stress and conflict on what should have been a joyful day.

We were also told the remaining balance would be paid after the reception, but halfway through the evening a waiter approached me â€” the bride â€” demanding payment as if we were about to dine and dash. It was humiliating and completely inappropriate.

After the wedding, the restaurant charged my credit card again for the flamenco dancers, even though our written agreement clearly stated that this portion was being paid by the best man, whose card information they already had. When I called to correct the mistake, the staff member I spoke with was condescending and dismissive, asking who I thought was going to pay for it. Only after I pointed out the signed agreement did they apologize.

Bottom line: they treated me like dirt on one of the most important days of my life. The food was fine, but the lack of professionalism, compassion, and basic respect left a lasting scar. If youâ€™re planning a small wedding or private event, go anywhere else.

Edit: I spoke with management after the event â€” the manager even admitted she feared our wedding was a â€œdisasterâ€ and offered a comped meal for my husband and me, which we declined because it didnâ€™t fix what went wrong. I was so upset itâ€™s taken me this long to post publicly, but their dismissive reply now only confirms my experience. This review isnâ€™t about compensation; itâ€™s to warn other couples how smaller events are treated at The Columbia. Their response only reinforces exactly why I felt compelled to write it in the first place.

By the way - a way to â€œplease meâ€ would be a simple apology. Guess thatâ€™s a bridge too far for the likes of the Columbia.

text: Absolutely iconic location and Cubano. Incredible experience if youâ€™re in Tampa! The history and food really shine through. Good potions, menu, service, and all. Simply beautiful.
Just an experience that you need to enjoy

I drove all the way from Orlando down to Tampa for a business meeting, and when my contact suggested we meet for lunch at Columbia Restaurant, I thought â€œWell, itâ€™s a fine optionâ€ but man, did she hit the nail on the head. From start to finish, the entire experience was extraordinary.

First, let me talk about Bobby at the bar. He didnâ€™t just do his job he went above and beyond. When I mentioned Iâ€™d like to try another soup, he immediately brought me an extra cup just so I could sample it. I chose their Spanish Bean Soup (rich broth with ham, saffron, garlic just the right comfort) and it was absolutely delicious. Later, when I needed to charge my phone, Bobby didnâ€™t just shrug; he handed me a charger and made sure every detail was taken care of. That kind of service is rare, and I tipped him extra without hesitation.

As for the meal, I had their Cuban sandwich, and it was stupendous best Iâ€™ve had in Florida. Tender roast pork, savory ham, melty Swiss cheese, crisped Cuban bread balanced perfectly. Every bite made me realize why this place has such a reputation.

Walking into Columbia is like stepping into a slice of living history. Founded in 1905, itâ€™s Floridaâ€™s oldest restaurant, and it spans fifteen dining rooms and over 52,000 square feet making it the largest Spanish restaurant in the world.  The dÃ©cor is classic and elegant: tiled floors, mosaics, rich wood accents, Spanish-style touches, and old photographs lining the walls that tell the story of generations. It feels timeless but with warmth.

Amenities are top notch: they offer free parking in one of two private lots (one across the street, one behind the building), plus street parking.  During peak times the lots fill up, so arriving early is wise.  Inside, thereâ€™s a full bar, private dining rooms, and on certain evenings, a flamenco dinner-show you get food, culture, and entertainment all in one location.  The wine list is legendary over 1,000 selections, with inventory exceeding 50,000 bottles.  The restaurant is open 365 days a year, welcoming both lunch and dinner traffic.

The location in Ybor City is rich with historic charm. Ybor is a National Historic Landmark District, with brick sidewalks, old cigar-factory buildings, vintage streetcars, and character at every turn.  Columbia sits on East 7th Avenue, right in the heart of it all.  Youâ€™re walking distance from the TECO streetcar line and the Centennial Park station.  After lunch you can easily stroll through Yborâ€™s shops, museums, or take in local murals and architecture.

In short: if you find yourself in Tampa for business or pleasure, Columbia Restaurant isnâ€™t just a lunch stop itâ€™s a destination. The ambiance, history, service (especially Bobby), and food all combined to make this one of the best lunch experiences Iâ€™ve ever had. Iâ€™ll drive back again just for this Cuban sandwich and to see what else they do that exceeds expectations. Highly recommended.

Used to love the LH! Iâ€™ve been a regular since moving here just over 5 years ago. Happy hour is over at 5. Sure it starts at 11 or noon, Iâ€™m not sure, but I rarely drink that early. Till they do, they will lose me to other businesses. I urge others to speak up with their â€œfeetâ€ or a review as I have.

Additional comment. Iâ€™m very disappointed to  see the Lighthouse owners have added a credit card use fee in the restaurant. I do not know if it is applied at the bar. text:
What can I say about this place to do it justice?  First off, when you call a German restaurant and the person who answers the phone has a German accent... you know it's going to be an authentic experience!!

Heidi, the owner of the restaurant,  greeted us at the door and was also our server.  The place is small, but cozy and the staff friendly.  We started off with waters and a pretzel. The pretzel was perfect, slightly salted, and came with a side of warm beer cheese.

For dinner I wanted the Sauerbraten meal, but Heidi talked me out of it! Instead,  she suggested I get the Bavarian Plate, as it has the Sauerbraten plus pork and a nuernberger bratwurst-which is their homemade brat made using a traditional nuernberg recipe.  I chose spaetzel and red cabbage as my sides.  I started with the Liver dumpling soup.  It was the most flavorful soup I've ever tasted, the broth was a deep rich beef base and the dumpling was delicious, a perfect size.

There were 4 of us that ordered, and Heidi made sure that we got what we wanted, with some really good suggestions sprinkled in.

The food came out within 15 minutes of ordering, and to be fair, I would have easily waited an hour for how good it was!  I don't think any of us spoke much until we were done eating it was that yummy.

There were some homemade desserts and I really wanted the apple streudel but I was just too full!  We plan on returning soon to get the pork shank. The pork shank you have to order 3 days in advance- can't wait!  Until then, Prost!

A little piece of Germany in the heart of Florida!

We had a wonderful evening at Heidi's German Restaurant â€“ and we were thrilled! The warm service welcomed us from the very first moment, and the freshly tapped Munich beer in a stein was a real highlight â€“ like a taste of home!

The cozy atmosphere, the lovingly decorated rooms, and the authentic details transport you straight to a Bavarian inn. What was particularly nice was how relaxed yet attentive the staff was â€“ you can feel the passion they put into their work.

An all-around successful evening, one we will always remember. If you want to experience a taste of Germany in Fort Myers, you shouldn't miss this restaurant!

text:
We found this Cuban restaurant through a nearby search while visiting Fort Myers for a show and decided to stop in. The atmosphere felt warm and inviting, the space felt lively without being loud, and the staff greeted us with genuine hospitality.

Our server Yeilys delivered outstanding service. She guided us through the menu, offered helpful recommendations, and stayed attentive throughout the meal without feeling intrusive. Her professionalism and positive energy set the tone for the night and made us feel valued as guests.

The food was outstanding. The presentation showed pride in the kitchen and for Cuban cuisine. Cuban cuisine is a favorite for me (Puerto Rican/Spaniard) and my wife (Dominican) and this meal ranks at the top for us. We were traveling with friends who had never tried Cuban food before and this restaurant introduced them to the experience in the best way. They left talking about the flavors and the quality of the meal. This visit set a high standard for future dining. We look forward to returning and recommending it to othersâ€¦and of course ending the meal with freshly prepared cafe Cubano is a must for coffee lovers.
